  "prompt": "Surgery: Where is the line between emergency surgical procedures that can be performed in the ER/ED and those that must be done in an OR?",
  "response": "The line between emergency surgical procedures performed in the ER/ED and those requiring an operating room (OR) depends on several key factors:\n\nProcedures Typically Performed in ER/ED:\n- Small laceration repairs\n- Wound debridement\n- Abscess drainage\n- Chest tube insertion\n- Cricothyrotomy\n- Superficial foreign body removal\n- Fracture/dislocation reduction\n- Central line placement\n- Thoracentesis\n- Paracentesis\n\nProcedures Requiring OR:\n- Complex trauma surgery\n- Major abdominal surgeries\n- Orthopedic reconstructions\n- Neurosurgical interventions\n- Cardiovascular surgeries\n- Extensive soft tissue repairs\n- Complex fracture fixations\n- Major vascular repairs\n- Tumor resections\n\nDetermining Factors:\n- Complexity of procedure\n- Patient's hemodynamic stability\n- Available equipment\n- Surgeon's expertise\n- Sterility requirements\n- Anticipated surgical time\n- Need for advanced anesthesia\n- Potential for complications\n\nSituational Considerations:\n- Life-saving interventions may occur in ER if immediate OR transfer is impossible\n- Some procedures can be partially performed in ER before definitive OR management\n\nThe specific boundaries can vary by hospital protocols and individual clinical judgment.",
